 people, such as the innocently persecuted Jews, sometimes individuals, such as violent and evil princes. The issue at stake here embraces all of society since it can only survive if a general framework is observed that is based in some way on justice and peace. But literature and the visual arts provide many examples of open and public protests against wrongdoings, ill-conceived ideas and concepts, and stark crimes, such as theft, rape, and murder. In fact, poetic statements or paintings could carry significant potentials against those who deliberately transgressed moral and ethical norms, or who even targeted themselves.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aMittelalter /Literatur. 4aMittelalter/ Recht. 4aStrafe. 4aVerbrechen. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCrime.  aMedieval Culture.  aMedieval Law.  aMedieval Literature.  aPunishment.1 aBeusterien, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBjaï, Denis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClason, Christopher R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoudert, Allison P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGough, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHahn, Stacey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJost, Jean E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomornicka, Jolanta N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLlewellyn, Kathleen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a